'''Cyclopia''' (also called '''cyclocephaly''' or '''synophthalmia''') is a [[birth defect]]. Cyclopia is [[wikt:characterized|characterized]] by a failure of the [[prosencephalon]] to separate the two [[orbit (anatomy)|orbits]] (eyes). This leads to the formation of a central [[wikt:deformed|deformed]] eye and an [[wikt:absence|absence]] of a [[nasal cavity]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1040589/|title=Case of True Cyclopia|accessdate=January 1, 2012|pages=307â€“311}}</ref> It causes can be either [[genes|genetic]], or as a result of an exposure to [[poison]]s.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chromosomal Abnormalities Assosiated with Cyclopia and Synophthalmia|author=Rufas O. Howard|page=1|format=PDF|accessdate=January 1, 2012|url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1311562/pdf/taos00024-0523.pdf}}</ref> The term "cyclopia" comes from [[Cyclops]], a giant one-eyed creature the Greek [[Greek mythology]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Developmental biology: from a cell to an organism|publisher=Infobase Publishing|page=107|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=G0wuFgQt8bQC|year=2009}}</ref>

